{"source_key":"sha256-618a8b40e5d2ae619ee8e272e58f5767","record_index":171,"record_hash":"sha256:eee90183ce452da4b8bf774bc4025fa3238bcb77dddd882c5da3b799cc23dd81","timestamp":"2026-05-20T19:27:34.681Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 988b1d\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2438\nOutput:\n# Agent Session Handoff Design\n\nThis note sketches the handoff feature that sits above the `but-agentlog`\nprimitives. It is intentionally not an implementation contract yet.\n\n## Goal\n\nLet a developer continue work from one machine, agent, or provider session in\nanother machine, agent, or provider session.\n\nThe target experience:\n\n1. work happens on a branch with agentlog capture enabled\n2. GitMeta sync moves captured agentlog data with the repository metadata\n3. another machine checks out or switches to the branch\n4. the user asks an agent to catch up\n5. the agent uses GitButler commands to discover and read relevant prior session\n   context\n6. the new agent continues with enough context to be useful, without pretending\n   it has natively resumed the old provider session\n\nThis is contextual handoff, not exact provider-native replay.\n\n## Current Building Blocks\n\nThe primitive layer can already provide the facts a handoff flow needs:\n\n- durable project-scoped sessions\n- capture turns within sessions\n- ordered transcript records within each turn\n- environment observations for each turn\n- GitMeta sync of the stored data\n- verified lookup of sessions related to a branch, review, or change\n- bounded hydration of related turn windows\n\nThat is enough to design an agent-facing workflow without adding product-shaped\nstate to `but-agentlog`.\n\n## Current Data Feasibility Check\n\nLooking at the live GitMeta database for the `agentlog-turn-storage` branch on\n2026-05-20, the proposed tools are realistic, but the data shape confirms that\nthey need to be bounded and metadata-heavy.\n\nObserved data:\n\n- 14 sessions related to the branch\n- 29 related turns\n- 7,357 stored transcript records\n- the largest main session has 16 turns and 6,037 records\n- the initial backfill turn in that session has 5,371 records\n- hydrating the largest session locally is fast enough for now, roughly 217ms\n- returning that session as full timeline\n[TRUNCATED]\nuntime, tools, model, or\nprovider.\n\n### Resources, Tools, And Prompts\n\n[MCP server concepts](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/docs/learn/server-concepts)\ndraws a useful line:\n\n- tools are model-invoked operations\n- resources are discoverable context\n- prompts are reusable user-controlled workflows\n\nThat maps well to handoff:\n\n- `sessions` and `timeline` are context resources\n- `records` is a read tool\n- a future skill or prompt can teach the catch-up workflow\n\nThe lesson is to make the data browseable and bounded, not to force everything\nthrough one command that returns a wall of text.\n\n### Context Providers And Repo Maps\n\n[Continue context providers](https://docs.continue.dev/customize/custom-providers)\nand [Aider's repository map](https://aider.chat/docs/repomap.html) both show the\nsame pattern: give the model compact orientation first, then let it ask for more\nspecific context. Aider's map is especially relevant because it is not the full\nrepo; it is a token-budgeted outline that guides later reads.\n\nThe lesson is that the handoff workflow should start with an outline card:\nsessions, turns, counts, agents, recency, branch/review/change hits, and small\npreviews. Full transcript hydration should be an explicit second step.\n\n### Review And Provenance Workflows\n\nDeveloper platforms treat provenance as a lightweight ledger, not just a blob of\nchat. Useful references:\n\n- [GitHub pull request reviews](https://docs.github.[REDACTED:entropy])\n- [GitLab system notes](https://docs.gitlab.com/user/project/system_notes/)\n- [Gerrit Change-Ids](https://gerrit-review.googlesource.com/Documentation/user-changeid.html)\n- [git trailers](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-interpret-trailers.html)\n\nThe lesson is to use stable ids and structured links. Handoff should preserve\nthe relationship between branch, review, change, session, and turn evidence, but\navoid heavyweight supply-chain attestation machinery in v1.\n\n## Research Takeaways\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T19:27:34.681Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}